<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth R. Weiss 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 D-DAY: Fifty years ago today, thousands of Navy Seabees swarmed the beaches of 
Normandy. . . . At H-Hour, demolition units blasted through the German 
obstacles on the beach so the first assault wave could land. Then construction 
battalions began building breakwaters and harbors. "They did all of this 
critical work at breakneck speed and all the while under enemy fire," said 
Vincent A. Transano, historian at Port Hueneme's Seabee base. Their role in 
World War II won high praise from Gen. Douglas MacArthur: "The only thing wrong 
with the Seabees is, there just aren't enough of them." 
</P>
<P>
 HONORABLE MOVE: Here's a switch. Instead of boosting perks as some politicians 
have done, Santa Paula Union High School board members have eliminated their 
own health benefits to help balance the school district's budget. . . . The 
board members must cut 10% from the budget, and forsaking health coverage saves 
as much as $15,000 a year, Supt. Robert Fisher said. "They feel that everyone 
needs to contribute to a balanced budget." 
</P>
<P>
 COWBOY WAY: The feds have trotted out what they consider a reasonable deal. 
But Ventura County cattle ranchers have branded it as something that could 
drive their herds off public lands. . . . Federal officials want to double 
cattle grazing fees in the Los Padres National Forest (B1). They also want 
ranchers to share the cost of protecting sensitive wildlife habitat from being 
trampled. But ranchers are suspicious. Said one rancher: "It's going to take a 
Philadelphia lawyer to figure this out." 
</P>
<P>
 SKY'S FALLING: Ventura residents who live on tree-lined Varsity Street are 
hopping mad over the mess raining down in their neighborhood. . . . Budget cuts 
this year prevented the city's trees from getting sprayed to prevent fruit from 
forming. So they pumped out a full load of dark-colored olives that stain the 
sidewalk and cars parked beneath them. At a meeting with 75 residents, Mayor 
Tom Buford got an earful about the threat from above. . . . The city's 
tree-spraying program has been reactivated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
