ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: IRVINE; 3 TEACHERS GET GRANTS FOR WATER EDUCATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Three Irvine teachers have received grants that will be used to provide water 
education programs at their schools. 
</P>
<P>
 The grants were provided by the Irvine Ranch Water District and range from 
$100 to $500. 
</P>
<P>
 Mike Buetell, a teacher at Rancho San Joaquin Middle School, plans to use his 
grant to create a drought-resistant garden on campus. 
</P>
<P>
 Students will plant greenery and maintain the garden as well as receive 
instruction in water conservation. 
</P>
<P>
 Grant money also will be used to expand the school's white paper recycling 
program. 
</P>
<P>
 Laurie Hekma, a teacher at Lakeside Middle School, will use her grant to 
create a three-week science program called "Irvine's Water Story." The program 
will include a hands-on ground-water model. 
</P>
<P>
 Gale Kahn of University Park School will use her grant to expand the number of 
drought-resistant gardens on campus. SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
